text: A quick rundown of the trailer for those that didn't understand it: An interracial couple visit the caucasian parents of the woman. A deer jumps across their car and is hit whilst they're travelling to her parents. A cop asks the black boyfriend for his id even though he was not driving. The black boyfriend meets his girlfriends parents and notices an odd presence about them. He is then introduced to the caretaker and maid, both of whom are black and give off eerie auras. He is told that they were hired to care for the grandparents of his girlfriend but carried on to work after their demise. He notices the black maid staring demonically out of a window, and the black caretaker runs straight towards him before taking a sharp turn, right before impact. The mother of his girlfriend asks him whether he smokes around her daughter. He replies with the promise of quitting. The father of his girlfriend then tells him that his wife can help him quit smoking with hypnosis. The trailer then cuts to a short clip of the mother stirring a cup of tea (a reoccurring clip throughout the trailer. Which we can assume has importance.) The boyfriend then denies the father's offer. We then see a parade of expensive black cars pull up in the driveway. Many guests arrive, all of whom are white and quite elderly apart from one young black man. One of the boyfriend's black friends back in the city calls him and tells him about a 'brother' then was reported missing in the same area and that he should be scared. The boyfriend then notices the back of another 'brother' (black man) at the guest party. He goes to greet him. As the man turns around he notices that he is the same 'brother' that was reported missing. He also has an eerie aura. The boyfriend goes to pound him, but the young black man shakes his fist instead of pounding it. The boyfriend then tries to take a picture of the young black man, as his was advised on the missing persons website earlier in the trailer. He accidentally leaves the flash on and the young black man notices. The young man then turns to a fit rage and his nose begins to bleed. He tries to attack the boyfriend tell him to 'get out' (title of the film).

text: This movie looks great and I'm actually happy a movie like this is being made. In our modern day and time we seem to have forgotten what true ignorance and racism is. Then a miraculous thing happens. A man like Trump is nominated for president and Jordan Peele decides to makes a racially charged film. From viewing his show, Key and Peele, this type of movie from him is not surprising. I'd personally be surprised if he made it about anything else! However, this movie is not racist in any regard towards white people. This movie won't cause the black people in America to revolt. In fact, this won't even stop interracial dating or marriages to decrease or stop. All this movie will do is uncover the undercover racists that live among us. Not every white person is racist, but as we've witnessed from the Trump rallies and even some of these comments racism is far from dead. Movies such as this one just show us as a society how much work still must be done for equality among blacks and whites.

text: Looks sort of interesting. GET OUT!!!!!! About a man who finds out the terrible truth about his future wife's sinister family!!!!!! "Now that Chris (Daniel Kaluuya) and his girlfriend, Rose (Allison Williams), have reached the meet-the-parents milestone of dating, she invites him for a weekend getaway upstate with Missy (Catherine Keener) and Dean (Bradley Whitford). At first, Chris reads the family‚Äôs overly accommodating behavior as nervous attempts to deal with their daughter‚Äôs interracial relationship, but as the weekend progresses, a series of increasingly disturbing discoveries lead him to a truth that he could have never imagined." Get Out is an upcoming 2017 American horror film written and directed by Jordan Peele. The film stars Daniel Kaluuya, Catherine Keener, Allison Williams, Bradley Whitford, Caleb Landry Jones, Lil Rel Howery, Erika Alexander and Keith Stanfield. The film is scheduled to be released on February 24, 2017, by Universal Pictures. The film has been described by writer and director Jordan Peele as "a horror movie, but it‚Äôs a satirical premise." Film's Plot: A young African American man visits his white girlfriend's family estate where he learns that many of its residents, who are black, have gone missing, and he soon learns the horrible truth when another frantic African-American warns him to "get out". He soon learns this is easier said than done.

text: If a white person said "I feel uncomfortable around large groups of black people" it wouldn't bother me... I don't get why it's so offensive to say the same but with the races switched.   Pretty much any human  being would feel strange around large groups of another race completely away from their own, whilst picking up on behavioural changes based on your presence. And can you say with complete honesty that you, your father and your mother would act completely normal around your sisters/daughter's boyfriend of a different race?Chances are it's a no or a *hesitant* yes... I understand that there is racial friction currently but should that mean films that talk about race shouldn't be made?!   '300' portrays the Persian army as barbaric and evil, yet they didn't cry about portrayal in a film. All races within thousands of films, are portrayed in a stereotypical way at some point. White people are not unique in this. Most - Not All - of the white people in the movie were portrayed as racist. Most films, white people are not presented this way... In most films you play every role you could possibly think of, from the suave intellect, to the witty superhero, from flamboyant pirate to respected father in a family setting and the list goes on. Guess what? Now and then a few white people will be portrayed as racist, just as black people will be presented as vile thugs and slaves sometimes. There are racist people of every race. To detest one film portraying a small amount of people from your race as racist, is absurd as it just draws from reality...

text: I don't know what to say about Get Out. It's a well-made film with some very good performances in it, but it fails to live up to its own potential. It offers a rather unique take on racism and what it can make some people do, but it doesn't treat racism as the complex beast it often is and chooses instead to make "sense" of it by treating it as a high-concept metaphor for white egomania.  Similarly, the very real horror of the misuse of hypnosis is largely squandered by literally having the main character smash a teacup. How much more effective wouldn't the film have been if the villains were a bit more difficult to overcome than that? Imagine if a snap of a finger was enough to completely control a person. How could you possibly "get out" of a situation like that?  But despite the film's failure to depict the complexities of true racism or fully explore the dangers of hypnosis, the film sails by on the strength of the actors' performances. Of those, only Daniel Kaluuya is consistently good, and in the hypnosis scene in particular, he's outstanding.  As for the others, Betty Gabriel camps it up in some scenes, while being extraordinarily effective in others, such as the "No, no, no" scene. And Allison Williams does a fine job of playing the girlfriend who's just a bit too good to be true.  So yeah, apart from the criticisms I've mentioned as well as the sheer predictability of the plot, it's not a bad film overall. Especially not when compared with the usual shit we've had to endure for years now. It's not a perfect film (as many critics would have you believe), but as a debut film, it's no slouch, and I will always respect a film that at least TRIES to be different and break out of the mold.  7/10. Or 3.5/5 if you prefer.

text: About a month or so before this movie came out I showed my mom this trailer. She had done her thesis paper in college about how comedians tend to have extremely dark sides to their lives and often use comedy as a way to heal. I showed her this trailer and said afterwards "Mom, I think this movie is going to be a big deal. Like I think it will change the game and set the bar for horror movies and will rank with classics like Halloween or The Exorcist." Because I knew Jordan Peele wasn't gonna allow the regular horror movie tropes to be in his movie unless he somehow made fun of them/turned them on their head because he's excellent at recognizing the significance of incongruity (being in comedy). So I was excited to see how he'd make fun of the tropes without completely losing the horror aspect of the movie and I gotta say this guy is a god damn genius and man am I glad he has an Oscar now. That is all.

text: Isn't it troubling that you, as a black director, like most black directors, have made yet another politically motivated film about race? Is this all black people think about? Racism? Don't you find it troubling and somewhat insulting that when an African American directs a movie in which involves race, that white people immediately give it positive reviews, regardless of how mediocre it is? Doesn't it make you feel that you are given artificial praise, just because critics and the media are so afraid of being labelled racist? Doesn't that say something? This film being scored next to Citizen Kain and higher than Alfred Hitchcock movies is absolutely absurd, yet it is happening. This is a form of affirmative action, to spare your feelings, not honest praise.   You aren't taking any risks here with this movie. If you wanted to take a risk, you'd make black people the "baddy", as we are all equal, therefore, any group of people, deep inside of themselves culturally, has the potential to be "racist". Now, that would be the "non-racist" view of course. Any race of people could technically be in the role of white people, but white people were in fact only lucky. Now, what I just said is the ultimate anti-racist thesis - A thesis in which, I don't think you take. I believe that you yourself are as bad as the racist white people you hate and it is made crystal clear when you write and direct a movie like this.   I just find it amusing, that people now see you as some kind of genius for producing something so mediocre, without seeing the fact that the real racism in this country isn't coming from regular blue collar white people, but from the upper class white people who rather do nothing but virtue signal and parade black people around as if your people are owned by the democrat party.   Now, apparently, you're taking "a shot" at white liberals, but then again, you'll go out and call Donald Trump racist (He's most likely a terrible president who says dumb things, similar to how terrible Obama was - who spoke nice, but was in the pocket of every major corporation in America) without any REAL evidence. So I think it's safe to say Peele, that you are basically racist yourself, and racist towards white people.   If you had any respect for yourself as a director, you would drop the entire "race" premise and go for something more human, because the fact to the matter is that you ignore any racism, except the racism that you want to see. It's an easy coercive way to get good reviews from guilty white people, but if you want to be truly remembered as an outstanding director, this kind of movie does a great disservice to not only yourself, but to other black people.   Do you really want to get a job or a position based on the colour of your skin and bad people feel for you? Or do you want to get recognition for something that you've actually earned. Because as far as I can see, you haven't earned a damn thing that people say that you have. Sure, you're successful, and obviously many people have heard of you, but the credit they give you for "the best film of the year", is an absurd joke.  This is an average movie at best, which has been done before 100 times.

There is no racism in the movie. It‚Äôs a bizarre world in which the white people admire black people so much, they want to become them. They are obsessed with eternal life and black people. It all begins with grandpa who raced in front of Hitler and a black man won. He then starts admiring blacks to the point it becomes an obsession. I didn‚Äôt think that the cheesy black airport police character belonged in the movie. The character reminded me of that black hacker from the Transformers. I don‚Äôt even think that Jordan Peele understood his own movie. You make a movie in which white people admire black people to the point where they want to become them and then you try to say it‚Äôs about racism? Huh? The original ending would have not made sense in the movie. The new ending, however, was just pure cheese. T...S...motherfuckin...A. I mean, come on. Overall, the movie had pretty interesting parts and was fairly interesting in general, but was nowhere close to what the comments are saying. It‚Äôs more like 7/10.
